			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Language Boxes: Bending the Host Language with Modular Language Changes</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LukasRenggli.html">Lukas Renggli</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcusDenker.html">Marcus Denker</a>, <a href="../profile/OscarNierstrasz.html">Oscar Nierstrasz</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_20">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_20</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> Language boxes provide modular, scoped language extensions to a host language—an integration/modularity contribution.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> They target embedding fine-grained DSL extensions into general-purpose host languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The approach includes tool integration concerns like syntax highlighting and compilation transformations.
</li></ul></li></ul>
